TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN=123456:abc...
ALLOWED_TELEGRAM_USER_IDS=123456789

# Auth: leave blank to use your existing `claude` login on this machine
# (~/.claude/.credentials.json). Only set this if the gateway can't read
# that file (different OS user, container, scheduled task, etc.).
# Generate with: claude setup-token
# CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN=sk-ant-oat01-...

# Optional: TTS voice replies. Required only if a user enables
# voice.tts.enabled=true in their data/config.json users block (default off).
# OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...

# --- Slack transport (optional) --------------------------------------------
# Leave all three vars unset to run Telegram-only. To enable Slack:
#
# 1. Create a Slack app at https://api.slack.com/apps → "From scratch".
# 2. Enable Socket Mode (Settings → Socket Mode), generate an app-level
#    token with scope `connections:write` → that's SLACK_APP_TOKEN.
# 3. Bot scopes (OAuth & Permissions): `app_mentions:read`, `chat:write`,
#    `im:history`, `im:read`, `im:write`, `channels:history`, `users:read`.
# 4. Event Subscriptions → enable, then under Subscribe to bot events add:
#    `app_mention`, `message.im` (and `message.channels` if you also want
#    the bot to listen in channels — currently we only react to mentions).
# 5. Install the app to your workspace; the bot token is SLACK_BOT_TOKEN.
# 6. Look up your Slack user id (Profile → More → Copy member ID, U…).
#
# All three vars are required together. With any missing, Slack stays off.
# SLACK_BOT_TOKEN=xoxb-...
# SLACK_APP_TOKEN=xapp-...
# ALLOWED_SLACK_USER_IDS=U01ABC123,U02DEF456

# --- App config -------------------------------------------------------------
# Behavior settings live in `data/config.json` — one consolidated file you
# can copy between machines to reproduce behavior. Layout:
#   data/config.json
#     users.<your-id>            ← workspace, permission mode, model,
#                                  voice, tz, name, notes (per-user defaults)
#                                  Keys: numeric Telegram ids OR Slack U…ids
#     sessions.<chat-id>         ← active sessionId, cumulative cost,
#                                  always-allow/deny tool rules, optional
#                                  per-chat overrides for workspace/mode/model
#                                  Keys: numeric Telegram ids OR Slack C…/D…
# Per-user blocks are auto-seeded from `userTemplate.json` on a user's first
# message. Edit `data/config.json` by hand or ask Claude — the bot watches it
# and the next turn picks up the change without a restart.
#
# Cron schedules stay separate at `data/crons.json`. Each row carries a
# `transport` field ("telegram" | "slack") so a cron created from Slack
# fires back into Slack and vice versa.
#
# Removing a user's block does NOT revoke access; auth is gated by
# ALLOWED_TELEGRAM_USER_IDS / ALLOWED_SLACK_USER_IDS above.

# Zapier MCP and other OAuth-based remote MCP servers are configured via
# the Claude CLI, not env vars — the bot's SDK inherits any user-scope
# servers from ~/.claude.json. To add Zapier:
#   claude mcp add --transport http --scope user zapier https://mcp.zapier.com/api/v1/connect
#   claude          # then /mcp → zapier → Authenticate (OAuth in browser)
#
# Google Calendar: when a calendar MCP is registered the same way, the
# bot's per-turn system prompt tells Claude to mirror meeting/appointment
# reminders into the calendar (in addition to scheduling the cron). Weather
# updates and other data-pull crons stay cron-only. If no calendar MCP is
# loaded, Claude just creates the cron silently — no error, no mention.
